ite anode. Simulations show that increasing Si doping from 10% to 20% LSO lowers the thermal runaway onset temperature T2, while increasing to 30% LSO raises T2 relative to the 20% case. Separately, at 30% SOC, LSO-30 exhibits an SEI decomposition stage (Stage I) between 137.3°C and 145.1°C that is absent in LSO-20 at the same SOC. Which conclusions are directly supported?","options":["A The non-monotonic T2 behavior with Si content arises because moderate Si doping enhances anode-silicon exothermic reactions while high Si content suppresses SEI decomposition and binder exotherms.","B LSO-30 is thermally safer than LSO-20 at all SOC levels because its higher T2 onset temperature indicates greater overall stability.","C The presence of Stage I in LSO-30 but not LSO-20 at 30% SOC indicates LSO-30 has greater thermal instability at low SOC despite its higher T2 in large-format simulations.","D At medium SOC (50–80%), LSO-30 shortens the time interval between initial self-heating and thermal runaway, suggesting a net safety disadvantage in that SOC range despite higher T2.","E The suppression of SEI decomposition in LSO-20 at 30% SOC is caused by the same SiF4 coverage mechanism responsible for binder suppression.","F Higher Si content uniformly delays all exothermic stages, producing a monotonically safer thermal profile across all SOC levels."]}},"ground_truth":{"correct_options":["A","C","D"],"option_judgments":[{"option_id":"A","label":"Correct","justification":"C005 explicitly states moderate Si lowers T2 via enhanced anode-silicon reactions and high Si raises T2 by suppressing SEI and binder exotherms.","error_type":null,"evidence_refs":["TR_Mechanism+38+UnknownJournal:C005"]},{"option_id":"B","label":"Incorrect","justification":"C006 and C007 show LSO-30 has worse thermal instability at low SOC and shorter safety interval at medium SOC; higher T2 does not imply universal safety.","error_type":"boundary overreach","evidence_refs":["TR_Mechanism+38+UnknownJournal:C